<author><name><![CDATA[Bregalad]]></name></author>
<updated>2006-01-30T10:20:02-07:00</updated>
<published>2006-01-30T10:20:02-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1034&amp;p=8809#p8809</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1034&amp;p=8809#p8809"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Question Related to CHR-ROM and CHR-RAM]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=1034&amp;p=8809#p8809"><![CDATA[
CHRROM and CHRAM are both on the card, and both are loaded in pattern tables.<br />The foundamental difference is that CHRAM is written to by the programm (the programm writes graphics to PPU $0000-$1ffff via $2006/7), but CHROM can only be read by the CPU or PPU. Because 8kb of CHRRAM doesn't allow much graphics, it is often larger and have to be bankswitched. Bankswitch CHRAM is possible, but in most cases useless.<br /><br />NB : The PPU has no RAM for pattern tables. The PPU just points to the chip that is on the cartridges (often trough a mapper), then the cartridge determine if it is ROM or RAM.<br /><br />The iNES header DOES give information about CHRROM or CHRRAM.<br />If the bytes that tells how many banks of CHRROM the game has is 00h, then the game has 8kb of CHRRAM.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=38">Bregalad</a> — Mon Jan 30, 2006 10:20 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
